  "text": "Because NQO1 was previously shown to be the dominant DQ reductase in normal bovine pulmonary arterial endothelial cells and intact perfused rat lungs (3, 44), we asked whether this was also the case for the hyperoxia-exposed cells. The data in Fig. 4 were obtained using the same protocol as in Fig. 1 , except that the NQO1 inhibitors dicumarol or ES936 were also included in the medium. When we compare the data to that obtained in Fig. 1 , several key effects of the NQO1 inhibitors are apparent. For both normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cells, Fig. 3 . Effect of DQ concentration on DQ-mediated ferricyanide reduction rates in normoxic and hyperoxia exposed cells. The DQ-mediated ferricyanide reduction rates were measured in the extracellular medium of normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cells after addition of 600 M ferricyanide and concentrations of DQ ranging from 1 to 50 M. The reactions followed zero-order kinetics, as in Fig. 2 , at all concentrations studied. The mean data obtained in the absence of DQ (n ϭ 3 each for the normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cells) were subtracted from the data obtained with DQ and the DQ-mediated ferricyanide reduction rates obtained by linear regression of the ferrocyanide concentration vs. time curves (as in Fig. 2 ). The symbols represent the DQ-mediated ferricyanide reduction rates (means Ϯ SE) for 6 normoxic and 6 hyperoxia-exposed cell dose-response curves, for a total of 33 data points for each cell type. The dashed lines represent the model (Eq. 9) fit to the data allowing for separate Km1 for the normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cell data. The solid lines represent the Eq. 9 fit to data assuming single Km1 for the 2 cell types. The surface areas of cell-coated microcarrier beads (means Ϯ SE in units of cm 2 ) used for the normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cell studies were 53.0 Ϯ 1.7 and 53.7 Ϯ 1.9, respectively. *Significantly different from normoxic cell DQ-mediated ferricyanide reduction rate obtained at the same DQ concentration (P Ͻ 0.05; t-test). . DQ concentrations were determined spectrophotometrically as described in MATE-RIALS AND METHODS. B and D: as in Fig. 1 , after 30 min of incubation with DQ or DQH2, the medium was removed from the cells, and peroxidase and H2O2 were added to the cell free medium. The fact that there was essentially no difference in the medium DQ concentration before and after addition of the peroxidase and H2O2 reveals that no detectable DQH2 was present in the medium surrounding the cells at the end of the 30-min incubations in A and C. The surface areas of cell-coated microcarrier beads (means Ϯ SE in units of cm 2 ) used for the normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cell studies were 46.7 Ϯ 1.7 and 45.6 Ϯ 2.8, respectively. The symbols represent the data (means Ϯ SE) for n ϭ 4 each for the normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cells with DQ (closed symbols) and n ϭ 5 each for DQH2 (open symbols), respectively. For ES936, 1 study each was carried out for normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cells with DQ and 1 each with DQH2. The lines represent the model simulation carried out as described in Data analysis. the inhibitors prevented DQH 2 appearance in the medium regardless of whether DQ or DQH 2 was initially added to the medium (Fig. 4, B and D) . Under these conditions, the decrease in medium DQ concentration seen over the experimental time course (Fig. 4, A and C) could be nearly completely attributed to cuvette binding (see Data analysis). The net effect of the NQO1 inhibitors was to eliminate the difference between the impact of normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cells on the quasisteady-state DQ concentrations seen in Fig. 1 . DQH 2 oxidation in normal pulmonary arterial endothelial cells and perfused rat lungs was previously suggested to occur via mitochondrial complex III based on studies with the mitochondrial electron transport inhibitor KCN [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Figure 5A shows that KCN blocked generation of extracellular DQ when DQH 2 was added to the medium for both the normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cells. To illustrate that DQH 2 was present during the incubation, Fig. 5B shows the DQH 2 concentrations in the medium removed from the cells at the end of the 30-min incubation period.",
